To install a package, you will have to use the install.packages(package_name) command.

To activate these packages and use their functionalities, run the command library(package_name). We will start with ISLR.

Run the 2 following commands:

install.packages(ISLR)

library(ISLR)

Introduction to ggplot2

For data visualization, install ggplot2 with the following command:

install.packages(ggplot2)

#The first graph we make will be a histogram of the S.F.Ratio column
library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.5.1
ggplot(college_data, aes(x = S.F.Ratio)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

#We can also assign different binwidths:
ggplot(college_data, aes(x = S.F.Ratio)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5)

#Density plot example:
ggplot(college_data, aes(x = college_data$Books)) + geom_density()

#You can also make a conditional density plot.  The 1st graph will change the fill of the density by Private vs. Public schools.  The second will split them into 2 graphs:
ggplot(college_data, aes(x = college_data$Books, fill = college_data$Private)) + geom_density()

ggplot(college_data, aes(x = Books)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) + facet_grid(Private ~ .)

#We can also make scatter plots:
ggplot(college_data, aes(x = Books, y = college_data$F.Undergrad)) + geom_point()

#Color the plot based on private vs. public schools
ggplot(college_data, aes(x = Books, y = F.Undergrad, color = Private)) + geom_point()

#Plots can be stored and called later too:
scatter_plot_books_f_undergrad <- ggplot(college_data, aes(x = Books, y = F.Undergrad, color = Private)) + geom_point()
scatter_plot_books_f_undergrad

#Last, we can add labels to our graphs:

ggplot(college_data, aes(x = Books, fill = college_data$Private)) + geom_histogram() + labs(x = "Number of Books", y = "Count")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Lets unpack what is happening in this code. First, we are creating a new dataframe called private_colleges (with the <- function). Next, we are calling the dataframe college_data.

The pipe operator, %>% tells R to look at the next function. The pipe operator is a function from the dplyr package. The function we decide to use is the filter() function.

Inside of the filter function, we are citing the column we want to look at (Private) and to pull only records where the value = Yes. Notice that when we are looking for values = Yes, we use 2 == signs. This is true when we are filtering on any exact value with the dplyr package.

Also notice that since the Private column is a string, we must cite which values we want with quotation marks around it.

Lets filter some other data based on columns that are continuous variables.

#Filter out colleges that only accept > 1000 students
college_1000_accept <- college_data %>%

dplyr also has a mutate function that we can use to create new variables

#Make a new column called "PERCENTAGE_ACCEPTED"

college_data <- college_data %>%
  mutate(PERCENTAGE_ACCEPTED = Accept/Apps)
summary(college_data$PERCENTAGE_ACCEPTED)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1545  0.6756  0.7788  0.7469  0.8485  1.0000
#Finally, we can layer dplyr commands on top of one another.  R will perform these commands in order, and they are strung together with the pipe operator:

college_data_full_dplyr_example <- college_data %>%
  mutate(PERCENTAGE_ACCEPTED = Accept/Apps) %>%
  filter(PERCENTAGE_ACCEPTED <= 0.50) %>%
  filter(Private == "Yes")
hist(college_data_full_dplyr_example$PERCENTAGE_ACCEPTED)

rbind() function: Appending Data

Sometimes, we may want to append two dataframes together. For example, assume we were given the public and private school datasets separately (they are currently stored in memory as private_colleges and public_colleges). If we wanted to combine these datasets into one dataframe, we could use the rbind command:

college_data_full <- rbind(private_colleges, public_colleges)

Merging Data

In this example, we will create 2 mock datasets and store them in memory as dataframes. We want to pull the data together into one dataframe for analysis.

#Create a mock dataframe called "employees"
employees <- data.frame("EMPLOYEE_NAME" = c("Alice", "Bob", "Carla", "Daniel", "Evelyn", "Ferdinand"),
                        "DEPT_NAME" = c("A", "B", "A", "C", "B", "D"),
                        "SALARY" = c(1000, 2000, 3000, 1500, 4000, 10000),
                        stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
summary(employees)
##  EMPLOYEE_NAME       DEPT_NAME             SALARY     
##  Length:6           Length:6           Min.   : 1000  
##  Class :character   Class :character   1st Qu.: 1625  
##  Mode  :character   Mode  :character   Median : 2500  
##                                        Mean   : 3583  
##                                        3rd Qu.: 3750  
##                                        Max.   :10000
departments <- data.frame("DEPT_NAME" = c("A", "B", "C", "D"),
                          "MANAGER" = c("1", "2", "3", NA),
                          stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
summary(departments)
##   DEPT_NAME           MANAGER         
##  Length:4           Length:4          
##  Class :character   Class :character  
##  Mode  :character   Mode  :character
#We can also find how many nulls are in the datasets:
sum(is.na(departments))
## [1] 1
sum(is.na(employees))
## [1] 0
#Or, we can find how many nulls are in a specific column:
sum(is.na(departments$MANAGER))
## [1] 1

We now have 2 dataframes, one with employee data and one with apartment data. Suppose we want all of the department names that the employees work for. We can do an INNER JOIN to combine the DEPT_NAME column onto the employees table with the following code:

merge(df1, df2, by = column_name)

For more on joins see:

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1299871/how-to-join-merge-data-frames-inner-outer-left-right

https://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/52230_5ae0d25125b544caab32f75f0360e775.html

employees_w_dept_info <- merge(employees, departments, by = "DEPT_NAME")

Changing data classes

Last, suppose we want to change the class of the data. For example, suppose we want to change DEPT_NAME from a character to a factor variable:

class(departments$DEPT_NAME)
## [1] "character"
departments$DEPT_NAME <- as.factor(departments$DEPT_NAME)
class(departments$DEPT_NAME)
## [1] "factor"
summary(departments$DEPT_NAME)
## A B C D 
## 1 1 1 1
head(departments$DEPT_NAME)
## [1] A B C D
## Levels: A B C D

We can also change departments$DEPT_NAME to a numeric variable:

class(departments$DEPT_NAME)
## [1] "factor"
departments$DEPT_NAME <- as.numeric(departments$DEPT_NAME)
class(departments$DEPT_NAME)
